comments.body:
Here's what I saw on ECC this morning:

* I ran:  {{euca-run-instances emi-3C263E7F -k admin -t m1.xlarge}}

* I saw messages in cloud-debug.log like:

{quote}
Wed Mar 20 07:52:55 2013  INFO [WalrusImageManager:Bukkit.4] 
[edu.ucsb.eucalyptus.cloud.ws.WalrusImageManager.getDecryptedImage(WalrusImageManager.java):1112] 
Waiting 600000ms for image to cache (0 out of 3)
{quote}

and eventually:

{quote}
Wed Mar 20 07:55:26 2013  INFO [WalrusImageManager:Bukkit.16] 
[edu.ucsb.eucalyptus.cloud.ws.WalrusImageManager.getDecryptedImage(WalrusImageManager.java):1126] 
Bytes cached so far for image appscale-1.6.8/image.manifest.xml :10737418240
{quote}

but the walrus kept waiting for the image to cache.  So I looked at some code, and eventually the database:

* {{psql -h/var/lib/eucalyptus/db/data -p 8777 eucalyptus_walrus}}

{noformat}
eucalyptus_walrus=# select * from imagecache;
{noformat}

Here, I noticed a pattern.  The "image_name" column contained mostly walrus object hex keys, but _some_ of them were suffixed with ".tgz".  _All_ images suffixed with ".tgz" had in_cache=f and size=0, while all others were cached successfully.  So I updated the DB by hand for the key corresponding to this image:

{noformat}
eucalyptus_walrus=# update imagecache 
                       set in_cache=true,image_name='ab6ae17a-06e5-4848-8ccb-eee5c72132b0',size=10737418240 
                     where image_name='ab6ae17a-06e5-4848-8ccb-eee5c72132b0.tgz';
{noformat}

The next attempt to run this instance succeeded.  So the problem appears to be in the walrus code that deals with converting names which include ".tgz".  Hopefully this is enough of a root cause explanation to lead us to a proper solution.
